description: From the earlier term Swedish turnip, because the Swedes introduced the plant to the English in the 1700s.

entries.meaning: (chiefly Britain) The fleshy yellow root of a variety of rape, Brassica napus var. napobrassica, resembling a large turnip, grown as a vegetable.
The plant from which this is obtained.

examples: Gotta be so careful nowadays; local copper's no problem but the cow from the council done me 'cos this almost brained a punter when it fell on his swede.

description: Coined by Michel Gondry in the film Be Kind Rewind, from the claim that films produced in this way were imported from Sweden.

verbs.description: swede (third-person singular simple present swedes, present participle sweding, simple past and past participle sweded)

entries.meaning: To produce a low-budget remake of a film without the use of professional actors or filming techniques.
examples: Chances are you've sweded something before without even knowing it.
